**********************************************<br>
<br>
So long have I longed for the coming passion to overwhelm me that I have died inside.  I remain now a withered shell, not able to do justice to the world that lies outside.  I contemplate the breath within me and I wonder if it would do any good to be expelled into the lives of those around me.  The emaciated thing inside me that others would call a heart beats slowly, ticking away the final moments that lie between decision and indecision.  I no longer respond to those who could reach me, for of late I have deemed it necessary to cease all but my vital functions.  And the captured soul inside me screams to be let go.  In agony, I must decide to now leave this place of mortal doom for that immortal plane or whether to continue on in the rough vestments of life.  The passion calls to me; the soul screams in agony; the heart beats on through the noise.  <br>
<br>
Desperate for the sanity to which I now cling precariously, I waver above the river of insanity that threatens to drag me away.  Should I drop into the melee below, or should I hang on, slipping farther and farther yet maintaining my appearances?  The river beckons me.  It calls a siren song of peace, of calm.  I know within me, though, that beneath the veneer lies a place of torment that I could no more bear than I can bear what I cling to now.  My fingers slip yet again.<br>
<br>
Stubborn pride within me sets a wall before my lips.  I could no more cry for help than a deaf man hear the cry.  And still the voices continue: the passion, the soul, the heart.  I struggle to hold on to this which I now call my life.  What a mockery is this.  Is life such that I should cling to it so precariously?  Is sanity that which I now am struggling to hold onto?  The waters beckon.  The voices call.  The pride builds the wall thicker, higher.  I slip yet further.  <br>
<br>
Then, a voice.  I look upward, straining to see the face of the one who is to be my rescuer.  He calls to me.  I see a hand, reaching, reaching farther.  I can not grasp it without letting go of this which I now cling to.  This is the test then.  Should I give up the security which I now have, waiting to fall and yet knowing my fate, or should I trust the hand and the disembodied voice which beckons to me?  Quickly now!  The time is short, and as I wait in my indecision, IU slip yet further.  And still there is the hand.  How can this be?  I look in wonder at it.  This, then is my answer.  A hand that can come to where I have fallen, a hand that can reach to me in my despair and desperation, this is a hand I can trust.<br>
<br>
Closing my eyes, I grasp the hand and slip away from the thread to which I once tenuously hung.  I drop instantly, plunging for the rapids below me.  In terror, I grasp for the hand, clawing with both hands for my salvation from the insanity below.  There!  It is still there, holding me, pulling me upward.  Then I hear them.  The voices.  They call to me.  They whisper my name: the passion, the soul, the heart.  They tell me to let go, to end this folly, to trust not the hand which now carries me.  Confused, I start to let go.  I look below to the rushing waters.  I look above to the face, a face which I can not see, blinded by the sun.<br>
<br>
Then I hear it:  the Voice.  It calls to me, drowning out the others in a melody so sweet I can not but drink it in quickly to satisfy me.  It is a healing water, a renewing flood that drenches my aching soul, my weary heart, and my confused mind.  The emaciated heart within me grows, swelling full to bursting.  Complete, the soul no longer screams in agony, for it has its rest.  And my mind, my mind can now see the truth.  I press upward, further on.  I want to see the face of the one who has called to me, who has rescued me.  <br>
It is then that I notice the slickness, and I look up in alarm.  Red stains my hand, a sticky wet thing that makes me recoil.  I realize it comes from the hand holding me.  Fearing I will drop, I cling harder.  But instead of slipping, I am brought on quicker and stronger.  The blood drenches my body, covering me in its cleansing power.  My clothes are drenched in the sweet red liquid.  I can no longer see the stains which once marked me.  They are blotted out.  Ah then, this is the one to whom I am indebted – the one who spilled His blood that I may live.  The rushing waters fall farther, farther away, and I now stand on solid ground for the first time.<br>
<br>
I fall to my feet, unable to stand.  A figure stands before me.  I gaze at the feet, pierced, the body struck through, the hands, wounded, the head crowned with thorns.  The power overwhelms me.  Who is it that must endure this agony and can still hold me and rescue me?  I do not understand, for surely no mortal ever accomplished this.  Like a lock opened, I now realize who this is.  My hero, my rescuer: he has heard the sounds which drowned out my life, the heart, the soul, the passion.  He has won, and I am new, and I am alive.<br>
